Mother Metcalf
Bangor Dec. 1886
Elyria
My Dear Children
I suppose you have heard of my being suddenly & violently sick with inflammation in chest - the Pleurie Liner (sic) & I don't know what not inflam'd (sic) right lung entirely in active (perhaps I don't express it right) But the pain was dreadful & the [words unclear] of brain in half sleep almost as bad - after trying Dr. Paine as was rather E. Cherie awhile he went for Dr. Mc[?] - He thought I might not live but a day or two - among other remedys (sic) they put flannel wet in boiling hot lineament or as hot as fingers could get it on to my side & shoulder from the 5th day it subsided very fast - and - b y absorption a very uncommon case the Dr. said especially in a person so old They wrote to C. he came & stay'd 4 days, walking &c with utmost solicitude O I have had every care & attention - What Children I have - was ever Mother so bless'd & Hattie so efficient - good & kind
Completed

now what shall I render to God for all his rich mercies - I will even as I have throw myself all impotent as I am unto his arms. - I have felt such peaceful trust - such quiet hope - O May it not be at last as the spiders web - Flow precious how beyond expression glorious to be in Christ & kept by him, when so vile to last without him
Now Anna let me caution you about your health - I suspect you have many times in years gone by taken medicine - when what you needed instead was rest - relaxation, from severe mental effort - by which means you have so injured the healthful tone of your stomach that you need to be comfort  I wish you [?] as much as in you lies avoid medicine you have a good constitution, try to keep it so
My cough & trouble in my side are almost gone I've only weakness & am growing stronger every day Do all write to you
Mother
Completed

Scrawled on top:
Mother
Jan. 8 57
Bangor Jan 8th /57
My Dear Son,
We receiv'd letters from you last night - which as usual gladen'd our hearts I did indeed get reliev'd when I was sick wonderfully quick - Dr. Paine came here 3 or 4 times & E. went twice to him for medicine &c. between Sunday morning & tuesday night - I don't know but I should have got better if I'd had no other Dr. but I think not near as soon - They didn't feel satisfied & got Dr. McRuen (sic) wednesday & thursday I was much reliev'd not withstanding both the Dr. thought as I'm told since that I could live but a short time probably my being so old was the reason of that opinion
Tho' it was so short a time it took away my strength & flesh - I have a strong inclination you know, perhaps you'll call it pride to take care of myself i.e. not to trouble other people not to be waited upon which came on a long even before I'm aware of it - But I probably got along all the better for it
I went down stairs or rather E. carried me in just
Completed

two weeks from the time I was taken sick (tho' not again for some days) and I sat up most all day every day - and have been gaining strength can stand by - am as well now as before I was sick except that my cough is not quite gone  I have had a cough and pain, or rather [?] in my side - not bad [?] the Dr. said by adhesion of the Lungs he saw it wanted near away & it does
I had too a strange sensation from the time I began to get better  I don't know as I can describe it - spasmodic or like hiccough or like catching the breath with a very sharp pain in my right side & shoulder - gone again in an instant almost but occurring at first every minute then at longer intervals till it has about ceas'd
It is wonderful that I am not so well - you and Anna & Nettie write about my going to Elyria - when Sam'l goes which he expects will be in April 
But I suppose it would not be best I shall then if I live be seventy years old - old enough to settle down at home for the rest of the time besides Allina expects to be sick in April  Almeda is in much affliction  Mr. River suffers I suppose very much It is difficult now for him to swallow at
Completed

all hurts him very much to swallow his food or talk probably cannot live long - & it will be even matter of rejoicing when he is releas'd & permitted to enter into the joy of his Lord to be where he is, and to behold his glory - I had a good long letter from Charles & Albina  they were all very well - sent us 2 prs of nice fat chickens  Almeda has a very hard disagreeable lot now besides great labor & care the every offensive odor in which she must live constantly  She is almost sick I fear it will mean her all out - James is boarding at Charles Everetts & attending school at the village I've had two letters from him lately he is making his calculations now to earn money as fast as he can till he gets enough to buy him a farm somewhere out west & make a home for his Mother & Linia - has given up the idea of learning a trade - I had a letter from your uncle [?] not long since he wrote that your cousin Sam'l Metcalf is in Illinois (a land speculator) Josiah has just returned from a 3 years whaling voyage.  Maria Stevens wrote me a few weeks ago that Sister Conard & Esther were well  She saw Sister Conrad
Completed

Bangor Jan? 15/57
My Dear Daughter,
I wrote a long letter to Isaac last week & directed it to Dr. cogan? perhaps it will not get there till he is away from there     not worth much if he never gets it no matters. My health is pretty good now tho' I am not near as strong as before I was sick. I have some cough and
Completed

Mother Bangor?
May 4 .67
Bangor May 4th,
My Dear Son
I receiv'd your good letters written when Sam'S was there & here I am yet feeling somewhat disappointed that I couldn't get to Milo before now. The Ice? went out about a fortnight earlier than usual & it swept off all the Bridges & Dams on the Piscalagais? The Brownville, Alder stream and Boabar? brook bridges- we have had a great deal of rain so that the Streams are high & the travelling bad yet- I expect to go there in a few days now_ I shall hardly get well Settled there before the time will come when I should like to go to Elyria if I could have a good chance- There are some inconveniences about living just 4 of five months in a place it takes So much time to get pack'd up to go_ & to get settled again_ indeed the last hardly gets done at all
Completed

you enquire if I would go to Elyria in June or July_ I want to be there enough_ But should have a short time to stay at Milo & Brownville_ moreover I dont know as it would be expedient or safe to go from here there in the hottest Season_ But If I go at all I must go when I can_ you speak of Coming here have you any business that will call you this way_ If you have I should delight to go back with you_ But I Shall hear from Sam's soon & will let you know what he says about his Father's coming_ The Eliab says that I shall not go with Maj. Furher + that he will go with me next fall but I dont believe he can till December
Maria is very well and smart is now gone down to Main St on foot a shopping Sam'S told you perhaps about Eliab's quick horse + how we got thrown from the wagon. E's wrist is very weak yet._ One night last week he left him just for a few minutes_ + he run & rid himself of the wagon except the forewheels and
Completed

was gone near 2 hours before Eliab found him_ the creature is just as quick as a cat_ But E. insists that he is perfectly kind_ They have not named the baby yet._ Charles has got a little Daughter born 24th of April
Almeda has bought Mills' part of the farm for $500, & he is expecting to go west_ is hoping to get a chance to work with you_ Mills has the western Fever the worst kind_ I fear he will be greatly disappointed Almeda's claculation as with a view to James's benefit_ Means to get all she can from the place + then to sell it or leave it & go west_ But a great deal seems to depend, with them all, upon whether you get located adventageously + even Eliab says he thinks he shall not stay in Bangor more than a few years Charles has been unfortunate with his Sheep some disease among them all sick + dying_ Almeda has lost one of her lows that she depended on for profit this summer_ C. has hir'd George Hodgskins for the Summer at 12,00 for? month
Completed

There seems to be, a more than usual, interest in the subject of religion in this City we have known of but few cases of conversion in the Central society but more in the Frewell Baptists_ Meetings in the Central Church 4 or 5 evenings in the week this 8 or 10 weeks past
How I do miss Samuel, from the singing choir? + every where_ I have felt rather uneasy_ no not uneasy exactly- at the thought of being here since he is gone, there seems not the same reason for staying here besides Maria has her two sisters + a strong Girl She dont need for sparry? or help?_ and it would be better for Percie now his Father is away
I have an opportunity to send this will not stop to finish it now good bye
Completed

Mother Miteall
Bangor March 14th 16
(Elyria Ohio)
Bangor
My Dear Son
The thing seems now to be determin'd that Percie + I spend the summers at Milo_ Anna wrote very earnestly for me to go to Elyria with Samuel but I have not been able to really think it best_ not that I should not enjoy it very much in deed_ I really cant think of such a thing as your going away from there before I see you
The question has been whether I could have any good opportunity to go in the fall but Sam'l has thought of a way_ His Father + wife are coming east to spend the Summer or part of it, + S. says I can go when they go back_ + so I can if I live + have my health_ but I had forty times rather have you or Eliab for company_ E. says he will go with me soon as the river closes but Sam'; says he dont believe he will or can 
Hattie presented me on my seventieth birthday a very handsome Silver apple knife and Eliab 
{side of letter} brought me a beautiful Gold pen & pencil but I had a nice one before that
Completed

14th,- Mr. Rider died last Tuesday [10th] was buried Thursday he has sufferd a great deal but died very easy at the last 
Sam'l & Eliab next? up to the funeral
I have written two letters to you within a month + am duily expecting one from you I should enjoy some precious privileges at Elyria or here and some comforts that I cannot expect at Milo- + indeed I expect many little anoyances there But I think it will be better for Percie to be these with the children 
He has not the goahead ativeness that Mayo had is babyish and charging round one all the time when his father is not about- he loves to be with him when he is here 
16_ Thus for I had written + then concluded to lay it by till I receivd one from you + now half past nine P.M. I have just read yours of March 11th & now what shall I say to you? I want to be with you + yours + Anna
Completed

at Elyria O: how much_ But I have thought that I ought to be at Milo_ Not as Anna seems to think because of my help I could be by way of Labor for I dont expect to do much any where_ + I am aware that it would make it harder for Albina. I think it would be better for Percie
I wish I could feel fully decided about it I think I should feel easier_ I had got the mama quite settled in my mind but Anna's and your urgent entreaties rather disturbs the puddle a little
Things doubtfull are uncertain + it is uncertain whether P. would be as well there in hot weather I think he has not entirely got over the weakness of bowels occasion'd by his sickness, or else fails to govern himself as he might (makes a great deal of washing of Pants) He improv'd in health + strength very much while at Milo + has I doubt not been more healthy during the winter than he would have been if he had not gone there
Completed

I expect Almeda here by stage tomorrow + will lay my letter aside again till after she comes + gets her opinion
Please write me immediately on receiving this + inform me when it is probable your shall have to leave him if you obtain the situation you mentioned_ Almeda came last night but I know no more what to say to you only that She is decided in the opinion that I ought not to go away this Spring_ If I could any way possibly think it best to go to Elyria this Spring I could hardly have time nor? to get ready_ Should want to go to Milo first- + he is going in a fortnight_ has nothing more to do but pack his goods.
Albina has a girl engaged for 2 or 3 months_ I feel as if it must be very doubtful if I got to Elyria whether I should ever return especially if C. should every go west + James should go west + consequently Almeda should go to_ +could I go + not go to Milo + perhaps not see the children + folks perhaps for years if ever_ Please write every thing _ plains all about every thing _ say if you can that you think it best that I stay till Maj. Furber goes- only I should dread to unclear with him. God bless you all my children I unclear to be with you- if I could only be in two places at once your Mother
Completed

Bangor May, 23rd /48
Mr Dear Children
I have written to you once I dont know but twice since I cam here_ My head is so confus'd that I cannot tell whether I have given you an account of the wedding which was Wednesday [19] morning at 8 oclock + the Groom + Bride started right off to Milo + Brownville + returnd Friday night_ They spent last evening here_ They expect to go to visit her Brothers Tuesday Wed. + Thursday and calculate to start for home Monday 31st a week from tomorrow probably be at your house Sat 5 of june perhaps sooner I long to know just how Percie has carried himself since I came away I am a little sad now a days I can spare Sam'l but tis like leaving my heart out to give Percie up to them
Completed

Still I know it is all best - best for him + best for me_ I have tried to do, to the best of my ability what Lucy so often + so earnestly requested me to do_ + this tho I have doubtless unclear often of doing right is my compensation_none but a parent could know the tears I've shed + how I've felt_ May God accepting endeavors + follow the dear boy with his blessing_ I feel thankful to God that I could have him with me so long_ And his Father I guess looks upon it as confering a favor_ Still I know it has been trial vexation, + expense to Anna + you + this you may say no- it is impossible a child for his age could have any family without & I feel as if it would be a happiness to me if I could make compensation But impotency is my inheritance and that which is not naught cannot be
Completed

Tis the Methodist Conference Meeting here now- All the Pulpits here + in Brever I believe were filled by Methodist Ministers today Professors Shepard + Harres? gone to Boston to the Meetings_ I have been but one morning + two evening meetings- Some of the family did go pretty constantly before I came but both the Children have been sick_ Lucy is considerably better _ Irwing is gaining some but is very nervous + unstable. They have to hold him in their laps all day long- have not bee able to get him down on the bed even when asleep in the daytime
Hattie + Mary are both here now Mary is going away to Binghampton next week in Company with S, + his wife- It looks cold + dreary here for the season but it has changed considerably in a week + another week if warm
Completed

will make a very great change Eliab has a Hal bed but he has not sow'd any thing in his garden yet- He has had hard getting along through the "Crisis" he says as the business turned out he gave Sam'l some 4000$ right out 
I guess he has get his business in pretty good shape now but it will take him considerable time to get his debts all paid
My expenses on the journey wire twenty two (22) dollars 
I paid it to Sam'l yesterday
His wife was dress'd very finely today richly + properly the wedding was in very good style I never saw her Aunts except a few minutes there, I was not pleasd with them at all_ She is very well spoken of as far as I have heard_ May Godbless you + keep you in the way-do write to me about percie, the meetings, + all the folks,
A. M. Metcall
Completed

Mother Bangor
Nov. 18 1858
Bangor Nov 18" 1858
My Dear Son Isaac_ Charles + I came here yesterday in the Chaise very comfortably that the weather is very cold we had a little Snow, 2 inches perhaps, on the 7th of this month + very cold weather ever since the ground frozen very hard it has it has thawed almost none at all even in the middle of the day since
I had a good letter from Anna written the same day that I wrote my last to her I receiv'd yours day before yesterday
In regard to Charlie He would be well pleas'd to go his Father + Mother would be willing his Father would be glad because it would he thinks be great benefit to him_ but there seems to be no opportunity_ Eliab + his wife intend to start their journey about the first week in Dec. And expect to visit
Completed

along at Hartford Easthampton Amherst N.Y. Binghamton + will probably not be at Elyria before the 20 or date? perhaps as the last of the month
I am sorry Charlie cannot go but perhaps it will be all best for him to go when I do if you want him I want Anna + the Dr. to think over the plan about coming here and write me as soon as convenient 
they are fashionable gented and tasty as dissimilar to the farm home as the antipodes but I can manage to enjoy it pretty well + amory the Romans to do as the romans do
But I think if I live a few years large I shall give up "packing up my dud" to move so often

Your Brother George is expected to take dinner with us thanksgiving day i have not seen him he has call'd here twice + they like him very much they say
Completed

Eliabs fine Vessel launch'd yesterday morning nam'd Mallie Metcalf loaded with ice for Havanna He recurs? $1800 freight money this trip_ The little ones seem to be very well now (you wouldn't think they could remain so with their low necks & short sleeves) Lucy eats such? heartily but Travery? not at all as I can see- but he drinks a good deal of milk
I am really sorry Charlie cant go, their school is just clos'd & a rather poor school it was + they are to have no more till next summer he really would be very useful to you he is so willing to work + is so honest + faithful + after all he is very dull about any book learning it seem as if he dont know enough to deceive it he wanted to but he will always find out the easiest and the quickest way of doing any work
Almeda talks of buying Charlies red house + it will be a fine one for her
Completed

it is so kind + so strong we came down in 1/2 hours in this hand travelling and the creature has been plowing all the fall_ Charles has got this fall work pretty well done I guess except his new ground which unclear till next summer he has 2 great stout ones getting out cedar for fencing think he shall try to build a Barn next summer 
please write often + tell Nellie + Anna to likewise
to your ever loving Mother 
Kiss the little boys for me + train them up in the way they should go
